CAPE TOWN - The Overberg proved to be the hottest region in the Western Cape during February, as it recorded more than half of the 41 fires that broke out in the province.The Department of Forestry, Fisheries, and the Environment’s Working on Fire (WoF) Programme in the Western Cape attended and assisted in putting out a total of 41 fires during February.The Overberg region remained the hotspot and an area of concern as more than half of the fires were reported there.Over 10 000 hectares of vegetation and forests were burned, of which the majority was in the Overberg. WEoF said ground and aerial resources assisted in fighting and successfully suppressing 24 veld and forest fires in various areas within the Overberg District Municipality.“Over 10 000 hectares of vegetation and forests were burned, of which the majority was in the Overberg.“Aerial resources flew for a total of 220 hours, and most hours were recorded in the same region.“Ground crews from various teams were dispatched 26 times, and the most deployed teams are based in Grabouw.”WoF general manager Melany Duthie-Surtie said: “Our resources, both ground and aerial, remain on high alert across the province to be able to render their firefighting services to save lives and protect the environment. The arrival of the three additional visiting teams has been beneficial. The two visiting teams based in the Southern Cape in George and Stillbaai have played a big role in assisting the local teams when they battled the Gysnmanshoek fire in the Garden Route.”Cape Times